We found that after 18 wk of age , female PGC-1  /  mice exhibit a mild but significantly abnormal weight increase associated with increased fat stores .
Lean mass was unchanged at the time points examined .
With further <termsem="GO:0007568"> aging </term> , a modest but significant increase in body fat was also noted in male PGC-1  /  mice ( unpublished data ) .
The basis for the observed abnormalities in weight <termsem="GO:0065007"> control </term> is unknown .
We did not find differences in <termsem="GO:0007631"> food intake </term> or activity levels in female PGC-1  /  mice .
It is possible that a reduction in systemic energy utilization , related to the mitochondrial dysfunction , leads to increased fat mass and weight gain in the PGC-1  /  mice .
Interestingly , an association between PGC-1 gene polymorphisms and obesity in humans has been recently reported [ 26 ] .
Clearly , future studies of male and female PGC-1  /  mice in pure-strain backgrounds over a range of ages will be necessary to fully investigate the observed abnormalities in weight <termsem="GO:0065007"> control </term> and fat distribution .
We did not find evidence for glucose intolerance or insulin resistance in the PGC-1  /  animals on standard chow .
Moreover , female PGC-1  /  mice were more glucose-tolerant and insulin-sensitive than PGC-1 + / + controls when <termsem="GO:0007631"> consuming </term> a high-fat diet .
